		Kitchen Scales
		</div><!-- page_title -->
		
		<div class="text">
		<p>
		Most of the ice cream recipes commonly available list ingredients quantities in standard English 
		volumetric units&mdashp;cups, pints, tablespoons and teaspoons, and fractions thereof.
		<p>
		But most of the recipes I'll be focussing on list ingredients by weight. And not just any weight, but 
		in grams, making a digital kitchen scale an essential kitchen tool.
		</p>
		<p>
		Actually, two different scales are required for this class of recipes. The standard kitchen scale available 
		at most kitchen supply stores (Bed Bath and Beyond, or Sur Le Table, for example, starting at under $10) measure in kilograms or 
		grams (as well as ounces and pounds), with a maximum weight of 5 kilos (11 pounds).
		</p>
		<p>
		This kind of scale is useful for measuring common ingredients such as milk, cream, and sugar.
		</p>
		<p>
		For the more exotic ingredients, the emulsifiers and stabilizers like soy lecithin, locust bean 
		gum, or carrageenan, a more <a href="medicalScale.jsp">precise measuring tool</a>a> is needed.
		</p>
